    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>service area business (SAB)</strong> is a company that provides services at the customer's location rather than from a physical storefront where customers visit. Examples include plumbers, electricians, house cleaners, mobile mechanics, and lawn care companies. In Google Business Profile, SABs <strong>hide their physical address</strong> and define geographic service areas instead of displaying a map pin.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">GBP share</div>
            <div class="tms-value">~35% of listings</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Max service areas</div>
            <div class="tms-value">20 per GBP</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">SABs follow the same local SEO principles as storefronts but face distinct challenges with proximity factors. Understanding how Google treats them differently is the starting point for effective local pack visibility.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a service area business?</h2>
        <p>A service area business is any company where the business travels to the customer, not the other way around. The key distinguishing factor for Google: <strong>customers do not visit the business location</strong>.</p>
        <p>Common SAB types:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Home services</strong> — plumbers, electricians, HVAC technicians, painters, landscapers</li>
          <li><strong>Mobile services</strong> — mobile mechanics, mobile pet groomers, mobile notaries</li>
          <li><strong>Delivery businesses</strong> — food delivery (own brand), courier services, florists with delivery only</li>
          <li><strong>Professional services</strong> — cleaning companies, pest control, security alarm installers</li>
        </ul>
        <p>According to Sterling Sky analysis, approximately <strong>35% of all GBP listings</strong> are service area businesses — a major segment of local search results often neglected in standard local SEO guidance.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's GBP guideline for SABs</div>
          <p>"If you serve customers at their locations, you can list your business as a service-area business. Service-area businesses can set a service area without listing a physical address." — Google Business Profile Help. Displaying a home address when customers never visit it <strong>violates GBP policies</strong> and risks suspension.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why service area business status matters for local SEO</h2>
        <p>SAB-specific configuration in GBP directly affects local pack visibility and compliance:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Address visibility.</strong> SABs must hide their physical address. Displaying a home address violates Google's guidelines and can result in GBP suspension — losing all local pack visibility overnight.</li>
          <li><strong>Proximity ranking.</strong> Google uses the hidden address as the radius centre for local ranking calculations. SABs rank strongest near their base and progressively weaker toward the service area edges.</li>
          <li><strong>Service area definition.</strong> Correctly defining up to 20 service areas in GBP expands the geographic scope of local pack eligibility. Businesses that skip this step miss entirely from searches in served areas.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitive dynamics.</strong> SABs compete with both storefronts and other SABs in the same area, requiring dedicated local landing pages to compete beyond the proximity advantage of local storefronts.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How to set up GBP for a service area business</h2>
        <p>The setup process differs from a storefront GBP in three key steps:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Select the correct business type.</strong> When creating or editing GBP, select "I deliver goods and services to my customers" to activate SAB mode.</li>
          <li><strong>Enter and hide your address.</strong> Google requires a real address for verification (via postcard), but it will not be displayed publicly. Check "I serve customers at their locations" and hide the address.</li>
          <li><strong>Define service areas.</strong> Add up to 20 service cities, counties, or zip codes. Your listing will show "Serves [area]" in search results instead of an address.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># What SAB listings show in local pack</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Name:</span> <span class="uf-new">Austin Plumbing Pros</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Address:</span> <span class="uf-new">Serves Austin, Cedar Park, Round Rock</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Phone:</span> <span class="uf-new">(512) 555-0100</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># No map pin displayed — service area polygon shown instead</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="types">SAB vs storefront vs hybrid — what's the difference?</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>Address displayed</th><th>Map pin</th><th>Ranking anchor</th><th>Service area</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>Storefront</strong></td><td class="cell-yes">Yes</td><td class="cell-yes">Fixed pin</td><td>Physical address</td><td>Optional</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>SAB</strong></td><td class="cell-no">Hidden</td><td class="cell-no">No pin</td><td>Hidden address</td><td>Required (up to 20)</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Hybrid</strong></td><td class="cell-yes">Yes</td><td class="cell-yes">Fixed pin</td><td>Physical address</td><td>Yes (optional)</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>A <strong>hybrid</strong> business — like a hair salon that also does home visits — displays its address and also defines service areas. Both the storefront address and the service area factor into local ranking.</p>

        <h2 id="examples">Real service area business examples</h2>

        <h3>Example 1: Plumbing company covering 15 cities</h3>
        <p>A plumber operates from a home office in Leander, TX but serves 15 cities across the Austin metro. They set up GBP with the hidden home address and defined all 15 service areas. After creating city-specific landing pages and publishing location-specific blog content monthly for 6 months, they appeared in the local pack for 9 of their 15 target cities — with strongest ranking in Leander, Cedar Park, and Round Rock (closest to the hidden address).</p>

        <h3>Example 2: Mobile pet grooming in 3 neighbourhoods</h3>
        <p>A mobile dog groomer serves 3 neighbourhoods. They defined those neighbourhoods as GBP service areas, collected reviews mentioning specific neighbourhood names, and created neighbourhood landing pages with unique content about each area. Local pack visibility grew month over month, eventually reaching position 2 in the Maps pack for "mobile dog grooming [neighbourhood]" searches.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">SAB local SEO vs storefront local SEO — key differences</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>SAB local SEO priorities</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>City/neighbourhood landing pages for each service area</li>
              <li>Reviews that mention specific cities by name</li>
              <li>Citations built in each target city</li>
              <li>Content answering "[service] in [city]" queries</li>
              <li>Proximity managed via content, not address</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Storefront local SEO priorities</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Physical address accuracy and consistency</li>
              <li>Map pin placement optimisation</li>
              <li>Walking-distance proximity advantage</li>
              <li>In-store experience content</li>
              <li>Address-anchored ranking radius</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for service area business local SEO</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Use a real, verifiable address.</strong> Google verifies SABs by postcard. Virtual offices and PO boxes fail verification and lead to suspension if discovered.</li>
          <li><strong>Define all 20 service areas.</strong> Use the full 20-area allowance. Choose cities and counties — not entire states — to keep relevance signals tight.</li>
          <li><strong>Build a landing page per city.</strong> Each service area target needs a dedicated page with unique content about that area. Duplicate city pages with swapped names get no ranking value.</li>
          <li><strong>Collect reviews mentioning cities.</strong> Ask satisfied customers to mention the city in their review: "fast plumbing service in Cedar Park." Location-specific reviews reinforce geographic relevance.</li>
          <li><strong>Build local citations per city.</strong> Submit to city-specific directories and local business associations in each service area. NAP consistency across citations matters even without a displayed address.</li>
          <li><strong>Post to GBP consistently.</strong> Weekly GBP posts mentioning service area cities signal active local presence to Google's algorithm.</li>
          <li><strong>Don't use fake addresses in target cities.</strong> Creating satellite GBP listings at virtual offices or co-working spaces in target cities violates GBP policies. Google detects these and suspends all associated listings.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — listing a virtual office or PO box</div>
          <p>The biggest SAB mistake is using a virtual office or co-working address to gain proximity advantage in a target city. Google detects and penalises this, often suspending the entire GBP profile. The correct approach is using your real address and extending reach through content, citations, and reviews mentioning target cities.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common service area business mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Displaying a home address publicly</strong> — violates GBP policies; customers don't visit, so don't display it</li>
          <li><strong>Not defining service areas</strong> — GBP shows nothing instead of "Serves [area]", limiting local pack eligibility</li>
          <li><strong>Creating duplicate city pages with swapped location names</strong> — treated as thin content; each page needs genuinely unique local content</li>
          <li><strong>Expecting equal ranking across the entire service area</strong> — proximity to the hidden address still matters; manage expectations and content accordingly</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring reviews mentioning cities</strong> — missing the simplest way to signal geographic relevance to Google</li>
        </ul>

